definition.value: A bacterial infection AE with an outcome of thypoid fever, a bacterial infectious disorder caused by the Salmonella typhi bacteria.
Typhoid fever is often contracted by consumption of food or drink contaminated with Salmonella typhi.
a urinary system AE that results in the inflammation (swelling and irritation) of the urethra.
a skin discoloration AE which shows a chronic skin disease characterized by portions of the skin losing their pigment.
an injury AE that displays a type of injury to flesh or skin caused by heat, electricity, chemicals, friction, or radiation.
a hematopoietic system AE which has a decreased erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR). EST is the rate at which red blood cells sediment in a period of one hour.
a skin AE that has decreased skin turgor which is the skin's ability to change shape and return to normal (elasticity).
A tumor AE that shows a tumor occuring in the gastrointestinal tract.
A bacterial infection AE that has the presence of pus in a bacterial infection.
A bacterial infection AE which is caused by Acinetobacter.
Outbreaks of Acinetobacter infections typically occur in intensive care units and healthcare settings housing very ill patients. Acinetobacter infections rarely occur outside of healthcare settings.
an injury AE that breaks the skin or other body tissues.
a tuberculosis AE which is an invasion of the peritoneum by Mycobacterium tuberculosis.
a tumor AE that shows a benigh tumor of vascular origin usually seen in early childhood.
a vascular disorder AE that has an outcome of the blockage of a blood vessel, usually with a clot.
a tuberculosis AE that shows an tuberculosis of the joints.
an arrhythmia AE that shows abnormal heart rhythms that originate in the bottom chambers of the heart called the ventricles.
A bacterial infection AE that is caused by Salmonella.
a blood potassium abnormal AE that has a lab test outcome of abnormally lower than normal amount of potassium in the blood

a necrosis AE, tumor necrosis factor (TNF, tumor necrosis factor alpha, TNFα, cachexin, or cachectin) is a cell signaling protein (adipokine) involved in systemic inflammation and is one of the cytokines that make up the acute phase reaction.
a tumor AE that that is a benign or malignant neoplasm involving the oral cavity and/or the lips.
a cardiac disorder AE that can present clinically as acute pericarditis, pericardial effusion, cardiac tamponade, and constrictive pericarditis.
a tumor AE that shows a benign or malignant neoplasm that affects the peritoneal cavity.

Representative examples of benign neoplasms include adenomatoid tumor and disseminated peritoneal leiomyomatosis. Representative examples of malignant neoplasms include primary peritoneal carcinoma, metastatic carcinoma to the peritoneum, and malignant mesothelioma.
an inflammation AE that shows the formation or presence of pus.
a bacterial infection AE with bacteria of the genus Mycobacterium.
a tumor AE that shows the most common benign spinal neoplasm, often located in the thoracic and lumbar spine, with a peak incidence of occurrence in the fourth to sixth decades.
a immune system AE that results in a state in which the immune system's ability to fight infectious disease is compromised or entirely absent.
a hepatitis AE that resutls in a hepatitis C viral infection.
a blood phosphorus abnormal AE that shows an abnormal blood phosphate level
a hematology investigation result abnormal AE that results in an abnormal level of albumin in the blood
an electrolyte blood lab test abnormal AE that results in an abnormal level of sodium in the blood
a blood carbon dioxide abnormal AE in which the levels of carbon dioxide in the blood is abnormally high
a rash AE that shows follicular eruptions characterized by papules and pustules resembling acne.

The term "acneiform", literally, refers to an appearance similar to acne. Acne vulgaris (or simply acne) is a long-term skin condition characterized by areas of blackheads, whiteheads, pimples, greasy skin, and possibly scarring.
A rash AE that is characterized by an eruption consisting of papules (a small, raised pimple) and pustules (a small pus filled blister), typically appearing in face, scalp, and upper chest and back.
Unlike acne, papulopustular rash does not present with whiteheads or blackheads, and can be symptomatic, with itchy or tender lesions.
an neuropathy AE that occurs when any of the twelve cranial nerves (nerves that exit from the brain directly) are damaged.
a cranial neuropathy AE which shows an damage or abnormality to the nerve that carries signals from the inner ear to the brain and is responsible for hearing.
a cognitive disorder AE that shows conspicuous changes in cognitive functions.
an neuropathy AE that is restricted to one nerve or group of nerves, or one area of the body
a vascular disorder AE that form in a blood vessel a clot (thrombus) that breaks loose and is carried by the blood stream to plug another vessel.
an injury AE that occurs in the cardiovascular system
a cardiovascular injury AE that occurs in a heart.
a heart injury AE that shows a laceration or tearing of the myoardium, which is the muscular tissue of the heart.
a cardiomyopathy AE that is characterized by a weekened heart caused by the effects of high blood pressure.
A hypertrophic cardiomyopathy AE where the distortion of normal heart anatomy causes an obstruction of the outflow of blood from the left ventricle of the heart
A hypertrophic cardiomyopathy AE where the distortion of normal heart anatomy does not cause an obstruction of the outflow of blood from the left ventricle of the heart
a cardiovascular investigation result abnormal AE that results in an abnormal result on a test used to evaluate heart function
a cardiac disorder AE that results in multiple cardiac defects.
an injury and procedural complication AE that results in a blockage of a device.
a procedural complication AE that occurs after the usage of a medical device.
a skin ulceration AE that has a combined area of ulcers <1 cm and nonblanchable erythema of intact skin with associated warmth or edema
a skin ulceration AE that has a combined area of ulcers 1 - 2 cm and partial thickness skin loss involving skin or subcutaneous fat
